          "type": "text",
          "text": "Perfect! ✅ **7-Segment Counter built successfully.**\n\n### **Wiring Table**\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Pin | Signal |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| D2 | Display | Segment A | via R_A (220Ω) |\n| D3 | Display | Segment B | via R_B (220Ω) |\n| D4 | Display | Segment C | via R_C (220Ω) |\n| D5 | Display | Segment D | via R_D (220Ω) |\n| D6 | Display | Segment E | via R_E (220Ω) |\n| D7 | Display | Segment F | via R_F (220Ω) |\n| D8 | Display | Segment G | via R_G (220Ω) |\n| D9 | Button | Pin A | (active-LOW with INPUT_PULLUP) |\n| GND | Button (Pin B) + Display GND | — | — |\n\n### **Sketch Overview**\nThe sketch counts 0–9 on the 7-segment display. Each time you **press the button**, the counter increments by 1 and wraps back to 0 at 10. The `displayDigit()` function activates the correct segment pattern for each digit using simple if/else logic.\n\n### **Power Budget**\n- **Per-pin (7 segments + button):** Each segment draws ~10mA through 220Ω resistor → ~7V drop safely. Button reads digital input (negligible). Total digital: ~70mA peaks (well under Uno 200mA limit).\n- **Total board draw:** ~75mA ✅ Safe.\n\nCircuit is ready — press the button to increment!"
        }
      ]
